{"questionId":"6260","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A positive pion decays into a positive muon and a neutrino.</p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage mjpage__block\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" display=\"block\" alttext=\"{\\pi ^ + } \\to {\\mu ^ + } + {v_\\mu }\">\n  <mrow>\n    <msup>\n      <mi>π</mi>\n      <mo>+</mo>\n    </msup>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo stretchy=\"false\">→</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <msup>\n      <mi>μ</mi>\n      <mo>+</mo>\n    </msup>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>v</mi>\n      <mi>μ</mi>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span></p>\n<p>The momentum of the muon is measured to be 29.8 MeV c<sup>–1</sup> in a laboratory reference frame in which the pion is at rest. The rest mass of the muon is 105.7 MeV c<sup>–2</sup> and the mass of the neutrino can be assumed to be zero.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>For the laboratory reference frame</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>show that the energy of the pion is about 140 MeV.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><em>E<sub>π</sub></em> = <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\sqrt {p_\\mu ^2{c^2} + m_\\mu ^2{c^4}} \">\n  <msqrt>\n    <msubsup>\n      <mi>p</mi>\n      <mi>μ</mi>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n    </msubsup>\n    <mrow>\n      <msup>\n        <mi>c</mi>\n        <mn>2</mn>\n      </msup>\n    </mrow>\n    <mo>+</mo>\n    <msubsup>\n      <mi>m</mi>\n      <mi>μ</mi>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n    </msubsup>\n    <mrow>\n      <msup>\n        <mi>c</mi>\n        <mn>4</mn>\n      </msup>\n    </mrow>\n  </msqrt>\n</math></span>&nbsp;+&nbsp;<em>p<sub>v</sub>c</em>&nbsp;<strong><em>OR</em></strong>&nbsp;<em>E<sub>μ</sub></em>&nbsp;= 109.8&nbsp;<strong>«</strong>MeV<strong>»</strong></p>\n<p><em>E<sub>π</sub></em> =&nbsp;<strong>«</strong><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\sqrt {{{29.8}^2} + {{105.7}^2}} \">\n  <msqrt>\n    <mrow>\n      <msup>\n        <mrow>\n          <mn>29.8</mn>\n        </mrow>\n        <mn>2</mn>\n      </msup>\n    </mrow>\n    <mo>+</mo>\n    <mrow>\n      <msup>\n        <mrow>\n          <mn>105.7</mn>\n        </mrow>\n        <mn>2</mn>\n      </msup>\n    </mrow>\n  </msqrt>\n</math></span> + 29.8 =<strong>»</strong>&nbsp;139.6&nbsp;<strong>«</strong>MeV<strong>»</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em>Final value to at least 3 sig figs required for mark.</em></p>\n<p><strong><em>[2 marks]</em></strong></p>","meta":{"questionId":"6260","referenceCode":"18M.3.HL.TZ1.6a.ii","subjectId":"46-dp-physics-last-assessment-2024","title":"show that the energy of the pion is about 140 MeV.","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"a.ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Option A: Relativity","Option A: Relativity","Option A: Relativity (Additional higher level option topics)","A.4 – Relativistic mechanics (HL only)","Option A: Relativity","Option A: Relativity (Additional higher level option topics)"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}